titlestmt.titleproper: A Guide to the Margaret (Peggy) McGrath Rockefeller personal papers FA410

profiledesc.creation: This finding aid was produced using ArchivesSpace on 2022-01-01 01:23:01 -0500.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Margaret (Peggy) McGrath Rockefeller (1916-1996) was a dedicated conservationist and environmentalist. She was married to banking executive and philanthropist David Rockefeller.

In 1970, Peggy Rockefeller founded the Maine Coast Heritage Trust (MCHT) to protect and preserve areas of ecologic value across the state. During this time, she also began to purchase and raise pure-bred Simmental cattle in Maine on Bartlett Island and in Pocantico Hills, New York.
In 1980, she founded the American Farmland Trust, using her experience in farming to build programs that focused on national conservation easements.

Peggy Rockefeller was also highly involved with the New York Botanical Garden (NYBG), where she helped fund a collection of books on America's wildflowers. In 1988, the renowned Peggy Rockefeller Rose Garden at the NYBG opened in her honor. She was also an active member of the Nature Conservancy, National Trust for Historic Preservation, and the New York Philharmonic. She also regularly contributed to many art and conservation causes.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Margaret (Peggy) McGrath Rockefeller personal papers consist of correspondence, personal files, and material related to various environmental and agricultural programs. The collection documents Peggy Rockefeller's activities in agriculture, farming, and conservation both in Maine and at her home in Pocantico Hills, New York. There is also a substantial amount of material related to the American Farmland Trust, Maine Coast Heritage Trust, and the New York Botanical Garden (NYGB).

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The Margaret (Peggy) McGrath Rockefeller personal papers are arranged into four record groups, each representing a different accession.

Series 1: General Correspondence. Series 2: Topical Files which includes 11 subseries arranged by subject/category: Personal Files; Carriage Drives; Trips; Parties; Gardening and the New York Botanical Garden (NYBG); Art, Music, and Cattle; University of Pennsylvania and Rockefeller University; Conservation and Preservation; Maine; General Files; Maine Coast Heritage Trust (MCHT).
Series 1: Personal Files. Series 2: Correspondence. Series 3: Bank and Engagement Books. Series 4: Photographs and Negatives.
Series 1: Personal Files. Series 2: Correspondence. Series 3: Maine Coast Heritage Trust (MCHT). Series 4: Environmental and Philanthropic Organizations. Series 5: Trips.
Contains four files of letters relating to the McGrath family,including correspondence and publications relating to Peggy Rockefeller's parents.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Rockefeller Archive Center has title, copyright and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them, and has authority to grant permission to cite and publish archival material from the collection.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The Margaret (Peggy) McGrath Rockefeller papers were donated to the Rockefeller Archive Center by David Rockefeller in January 2011.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Special format items have been separated from the body of the collection and assigned a unique separation number, as noted. Requests to access open special formats should reference the unique separation number.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.
